  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n---\n## 2026-04-25 01:34 UTC \u2014 [P4: Alpha Research] Test the Momentum-Quality Hypothesis Inside High-Bias Trades So We Can Tell Whether MACD, Not Bias Alone, Explains the Extreme-Band Failures\n\n**Task:** Compare MACD strength in the profitable `55-64.9` bias band versus the weaker `65+` band inside the surviving live hour set, using SolSt1ne\u2019s emphasis on signal quality rather than raw conviction alone.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- In the surviving `11/12/20` and `v5a_pass` sample:\n  - `55-64.9` band: `6` trades, MACD abs avg `9.697`\n    - winners MACD abs avg `11.238`\n    - loser MACD abs avg `1.994`\n  - `65-80` band: `3` trades, MACD abs avg `9.565`\n    - lone winner MACD abs `18.616`\n    - losers MACD abs avg `5.040`\n- So average MACD across the two bands is similar overall, but **the winners consistently have much stronger MACD than the losers**, especially in the extreme-bias bucket.\n- This matches SolSt1ne\u2019s broader lesson: signal quality matters more than raw score magnitude.\n\n**My thinking:**\nI\u2019m more convinced now that the high-bias issue is not \u201cextreme bias bad.\u201d It is \u201cextreme bias without strong momentum confirmation is dangerous.\u201d That is a much better research direction than fiddling with the bias cap alone. If we ever tighten this logic, MACD-strength gating inside the upper bias band is the more credible lever.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Keep the bias cap unchanged for now.\n- Treat **MACD quality as the leading candidate** for any future refinement of `65+` trades.\n\n**Next:** On the next P4 heartbeat, test a simple shadow rule like \u201crequire stronger MACD for `|bias| >= 65`\u201d against the tiny current sample and record whether it would have filtered both losers while preserving the winner.\n\n## 2026-04-25 01:33 UTC \u2014 [P3: Strategy Development] Inspect the Three Surviving 65+ Bias Trades So We Can Tell Whether the High-Bias Danger Zone Has a Common Failure Signature or Is Just Tiny-Sample Noise\n\n**Task:** Isolate the three surviving `|bias| >= 65` trades in the live `11/12/20` structure and check for shared hour, cooldown, OBI, or momentum patterns.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- The three surviving `65+` trades are:\n  - `2026-04-01 20:05 UTC` \u2014 **loss** at `hour 20`, `bias -65.8`, `cooldown BLOCK`, `obi -0.228`, `macd -7.77`\n  - `2026-04-03 12:40 UTC` \u2014 **win** at `hour 12`, `bias -69.8`, `cooldown BLOCK`, `obi -0.491`, `macd -18.62`\n  - `2026-04-06 12:10 UTC` \u2014 **loss** at `hour 12`, `bias -66.8`, `cooldown PASS`, `obi -0.614`, `macd -2.31`\n- There is **no clean cooldown explanation**:\n  - losses occurred once with `BLOCK` and once with `PASS`\n- There is also **no clean hour explanation**:\n  - one loss at `20`, one loss at `12`, one win at `12`\n- The best hint is indicator quality:\n  - the lone winner had the **strongest downside momentum** (`macd -18.62`) without the extreme OBI boost condition\n  - the losing `BOOST` case had the weakest MA",
